For a hollow circle, you can use a simple `div` with rounded corners and only a border. Here's a simple example to illustrate both concepts in a basic manner - drawing a hollow circle and a rough approximation of a star using HTML and CSS:

```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html>
<head>
    <title>Star and Circle</title>
    <style>
        .circle {
            width: 100px;
            height: 100px;
            border-radius: 50%;
            border: 2px solid #800080;
        }
        .line {
            height: 2px;
            background-color: #800080;
            position: absolute;
            transform-origin: 0% 0%;
        }
        .line1 { width: 60px; transform: rotate(18deg); top: 40px; left: 20px; }
        .line2 { width: 60px; transform: rotate(-18deg); top: 40px; left: 20px; }
        .line3 { width: 60px; transform: rotate(54deg); top: 8px; left: 45px; }
        .line4 { width: 60px; transform: rotate(-54deg); top: 8px; right: 45px; }
        .line5 { width: 60px; top: 68px; left: 20px; }
    </style>
</head>
<body>

<div class="circle"></div>
<div class="line line1"></div>
<div class="line line2"></div>
<div class="line line3"></div>
<div class="line line4"></div>
<div class="line line5"></div>

</body>
</html>
```

